# Engineering an Indie Game — Part 2  
### The First Mistake I Avoided When Starting the Project

When I decided to build a game, I knew something important:

Most indie games never ship.

Not because the developers lack talent.

But because the scope quietly grows until the project becomes impossible to finish.

Open-world ideas.
Procedural systems.
Endless content.
Perfect graphics.

The dream game keeps expanding.

At some point the project collapses under its own ambition.

I wanted to avoid that trap from the very beginning.

Some of my early design notes looked something like this:

![Early Game Structure Diagram](/assets/earlyGameStructureDiagram.png "Early Game Structure Diagram")

And like most game ideas, it could easily grow from there.

More towers.
More regions.
More systems.

That’s exactly where many projects lose control of scope.

So before writing any real code, I forced myself to answer a simple question:

**What is the smallest version of this game that would still feel complete?**

Not a demo.

Not a prototype.

A **complete game** — just smaller.

That constraint shaped almost every design decision that followed.

If the game had to stay small, then every system needed to justify its existence.

Instead of designing a massive world, I started thinking about **tight systems**:

- a small town that feels alive
- a dungeon structure that encourages exploration
- progression that rewards curiosity
- mechanics that interact in interesting ways

The goal isn't to build a huge game.

The goal is to build a **coherent one**.

As a software engineer, this felt surprisingly familiar.

In large systems, uncontrolled scope leads to fragile architecture and endless delays.

Games are no different.

So the first rule of this project became simple:

**Scope is a design decision.**

Everything else grows from there.

In the next part, I’ll talk about how defining the **core gameplay loop** helped turn that constraint into an actual game design.

